---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";

const title = "How to Save Income Tax in India 2024-25: Complete Guide";
const description = "Learn how to save income tax in India for FY 2024-25. Discover tax-saving investments, deductions under Section 80C, 80D, HRA exemption, and compare old vs new tax regime to maximize your tax savings.";
const image = "/images/blogs/tax-saving-guide-2024.jpg";
const author = "Nora Chen";
const lastUpdated = "July 2026";
const readTime = "15 min read";
const canonical = "https://taxportal.com/blogs/how-to-save-income-tax-india-2024-25";
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} image={image}>
  <div class="min-h-screen bg-canvas dark:bg-primary">
    <main class="min-h-screen">
      <div class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-4 py-16 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <nav aria-label="Breadcrumb" class="mb-6 text-sm">
          <ol class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-2">
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><a href="/" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Home</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted" aria-hidden="true">/</span><a href="/blogs" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">Tax Guides</a></li>
            <li class="flex items-center gap-2"><span class="text-muted" aria-hidden="true">/</span><span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary" aria-current="page">How to Save Income Tax in India 2024-25</span></li>
          </ol>
        </nav>

        <article class="prose max-w-none">
          <header class="mb-8">
            <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">{title}</h1>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-4 text-sm text-muted dark:text-muted">
              <span>By <span class="font-medium text-ink dark:text-on-primary">{author}</span></span>
              <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
              <span>Last updated: {lastUpdated}</span>
              <span aria-hidden="true">·</span>
              <span>{readTime}</span>
            </div>
            <div class="mt-4 rounded-lg border border-hairline bg-canvas p-4 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary">
              <p class="text-sm text-body dark:text-muted"><strong>Editorial Review:</strong> This guide has been reviewed for accuracy against the Income Tax Act provisions for FY 2024-25 (AY 2025-26).</p>
            </div>
          </header>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-6 text-body dark:text-muted">
            <p>Tax planning is an essential part of financial planning for every Indian taxpayer. Understanding how to save income tax helps you keep more of your hard-earned money while building long-term wealth. This comprehensive guide covers every available tax-saving option under both the old and new tax regimes for FY 2024-25.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Old vs New Tax Regime: Which One Should You Choose?</h2>
            <p>The first and most critical decision you need to make is whether to opt for the old tax regime or the new tax regime. The old regime allows you to claim various deductions and exemptions, while the new regime offers lower tax rates but limits most deductions. For salaried individuals, the new regime became the default from FY 2023-24 onwards, but you can still opt for the old regime if it proves more beneficial.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">New Tax Regime Slabs FY 2024-25</h3>
            <p>The new tax regime for FY 2024-25 (AY 2025-26) offers the following slab rates for individuals below 60 years:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Up to ₹4 lakh: Nil</li>
              <li>₹4 lakh to ₹8 lakh: 5%</li>
              <li>₹8 lakh to ₹12 lakh: 10%</li>
              <li>₹12 lakh to ₹16 lakh: 15%</li>
              <li>₹16 lakh to ₹20 lakh: 20%</li>
              <li>₹20 lakh to ₹24 lakh: 25%</li>
              <li>Above ₹24 lakh: 30%</li>
            </ul>
            <p>A standard deduction of ₹75,000 is available for salaried individuals under the new regime. The rebate under Section 87A has been increased to ₹25,000 for incomes up to ₹7 lakh, making the new regime effectively tax-free up to that limit.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Old Tax Regime Slabs FY 2024-25</h3>
            <p>The old tax regime maintains the traditional slab structure with lower rates but allows deductions under Sections 80C, 80D, HRA, and more.</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Up to ₹2.5 lakh: Nil</li>
              <li>₹2.5 lakh to ₹5 lakh: 5%</li>
              <li>₹5 lakh to ₹10 lakh: 20%</li>
              <li>Above ₹10 lakh: 30%</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Top Tax-Saving Investments Under Section 80C</h2>
            <p>Section 80C is the most popular tax-saving section, allowing deductions up to ₹1.5 lakh. Here are the best investment options for FY 2024-25:</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">1. Employee Provident Fund (EPF)</h3>
            <p>EPF is the mandatory retirement savings scheme for salaried employees. Your contribution to EPF qualifies for deduction under Section 80C. For many employees, EPF alone can exhaust the ₹1.5 lakh 80C limit.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">2. Public Provident Fund (PPF)</h3>
            <p>PPF is a government-backed savings scheme with a lock-in period of 15 years. It offers compound interest and is completely tax-free. The current interest rate is around 7.1% per annum.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">3. Equity Linked Savings Scheme (ELSS)</h3>
            <p>ELSS funds are diversified equity mutual funds with a 3-year lock-in period. They offer the potential for higher returns compared to traditional tax-saving instruments. ELSS is ideal for investors with a moderate to high risk appetite.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">4. National Pension System (NPS)</h3>
            <p>NPS is a voluntary, defined contribution, long-term retirement savings scheme. You can claim an additional deduction of up to ₹50,000 under Section 80CCD(1B) over and above the ₹1.5 lakh limit of Section 80C.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">5. Life Insurance Premiums</h3>
            <p>Premiums paid for life insurance policies for yourself, spouse, or children qualify for deduction under Section 80C. The premium should not exceed 10% of the sum assured for policies issued after March 31, 2012.</p>

            <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">6. Home Loan Principal Repayment</h3>
            <p>The principal amount paid towards home loan repayment qualifies for deduction under Section 80C. This includes payments made for purchase, construction, or renovation of a residential property.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Section 80D: Health Insurance Premiums</h2>
            <p>Section 80D allows you to claim deductions for health insurance premiums paid for yourself, spouse, dependent children, and parents:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Self, spouse, and children: Up to ₹25,000</li>
              <li>Parents below 60 years: Up to ₹25,000</li>
              <li>Parents above 60 years: Up to ₹50,000</li>
              <li>Additional deduction for senior citizens: Up to ₹50,000</li>
            </ul>
            <p>If you pay health insurance for both your parents and your own family, you can claim a total deduction of up to ₹75,000, or ₹1,00,000 if all covered are senior citizens.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">HRA Exemption</h2>
            <p>House Rent Allowance (HRA) is a common component of salary. Under Section 10(13A), you can claim exemption on HRA received from your employer. The exemption is calculated as the lowest of:</p>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Actual HRA received</li>
              <li>50% of basic salary for metro cities (Delhi, Mumbai, Chennai, Kolkata) or 40% for non-metro cities</li>
              <li>Rent paid minus 10% of basic salary</li>
            </ul>
            <p>Use our <a href="/countries/india/income-tax/income-tax-calculator">income tax calculator</a> to determine your HRA exemption and maximize your tax savings. Ensure you maintain rent receipts, a valid rent agreement, and your landlord's PAN if annual rent exceeds ₹1 lakh.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Home Loan Tax Benefits</h2>
            <p>Home loans offer dual tax benefits. Under Section 24, you can claim deduction for interest paid on the home loan up to ₹2 lakh for a self-occupied property (no limit for let-out properties). Under Section 80C, the principal repayment qualifies for deduction up to ₹1.5 lakh.</p>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Common Tax-Saving Mistakes to Avoid</h2>
            <ul class="list-disc pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Not claiming HRA exemption correctly or failing to submit rent receipts to your employer.</li>
              <li>Investing in 80C at the last minute without proper planning.</li>
              <li>Not comparing old vs new regime before choosing.</li>
              <li>Forgetting to claim home loan benefits for interest and principal.</li>
              <li>Not saving rent receipts and landlord PAN for HRA claims.</li>
              <li>Claiming deductions without proper documentation.</li>
              <li>Not reviewing and updating tax-saving investments annually.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Tax Planning Checklist for FY 2024-25</h2>
            <ol class="list-decimal pl-6 space-y-2">
              <li>Compare old vs new tax regime using our income tax calculator.</li>
              <li>Invest in ELSS, PPF, or NPS to maximize Section 80C deductions.</li>
              <li>Buy health insurance for yourself and parents under Section 80D.</li>
              <li>Claim HRA exemption with proper rent receipts and landlord PAN.</li>
              <li>Utilize home loan benefits for interest and principal.</li>
              <li>Plan additional investments in NPS for the extra ₹50,000 deduction.</li>
              <li>Keep all investment proofs and receipts for audit.</li>
              <li>File ITR before the due date to avoid penalties under Sections 234A, 234B, and 234C.</li>
            </ol>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-ink dark:text-on-primary">Conclusion</h2>
            <p>Tax planning is not just about saving tax—it is about making smart financial decisions that align with your goals. By understanding the available deductions, choosing the right tax regime, and investing wisely, you can significantly reduce your tax burden while building wealth for the future. Use our free <a href="/countries/india/income-tax/income-tax-calculator">Indian income tax calculator</a> to estimate your tax liability under both regimes and make an informed decision.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <aside class="mt-12 rounded-xl border border-hairline bg-canvas-soft p-6 dark:border-white/15 dark:bg-primary" aria-label="Related calculators">
          <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-ink mb-4 dark:text-on-primary">Related Calculators</h3>
          <div class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-3 sm:grid-cols-2">
            <a href="/countries/india/income-tax/income-tax-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">India Income Tax Calculator</a>
            <a href="/countries/india/gst/gst-calculator" class="text-link hover:underline dark:text-link">India GST Calculator</a>
          </div>
        </aside>
      </div>
    </main>
  </div>
</Layout>